            <ArticleTitle>Mid-infrared long-pass filter for high-power applications based on grating diffraction.</ArticleTitle>
            <Pagination>
                <MedlinePgn>3014-3017</MedlinePgn>
            </Pagination>
            <ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1364/OL.44.003014</ELocationID>
            <Abstract>
                <AbstractText>A gold-coated silicon grating has been developed, enabling efficient spatial separation of broadband mid-infrared (MIR) beams with wavelengths &gt;5  μm from collinearly propagating, broadband, high-power light in the near-infrared (NIR) spectral range (centered at 2 μm). The optic provides spectral filtering at high powers in a thermally robust and chromatic-dispersion-free manner such as that necessary for coherent MIR radiation sources based on parametric frequency downconversion of femtosecond NIR lasers. The suppression of a &gt;20  W average-power, 2 μm driving pulse train by three orders of magnitude, while retaining high reflectivity of the broadband MIR beam, is presented.</AbstractText>
            </Abstract>
